            "attributes": {
                "title": "SDOs as de facto do-ocracies — how standards are really made",
                "slug": "sdos-as-de-facto-do-ocracies-how-standards-are-really-made",
                "blurb": {
                    "html": "<p>This talk was given at the &quot;Decision-making in standard developing organisations for the internet&quot; workshop at the University of Warwick's Brussels office in April 2017.</p>\n<p>It explores how Web standards are actually developed in practice, and how technological changes in the way browsers are built, distributed, and licensed has impacted the role of standard organisations.</p>\n"
                },
                "slidedeck": {
                    "data": [
                        {
                            "id": "sd_1938",
                            "type": "images",
                            "slides": [
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_bITsyF",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>SDOs as de facto do-ocracies How standards are really made</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-0.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_DcCgqe",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>About me • • • •\nStarted in open-source and the web. 3+ yr stint as Facebook’s W3C AC Rep. Lead testing at W3C. Now consultant for browser vendors + editor of the Generic Sensor API and WebIDL.\nGenerally @tobie around the web. tobie@codespeaks.com</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-1.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_pvvUj3",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>Web SDOs • • • •\nW3C (pretty much all web APIs) Ecma international (JavaScript) Khronos (WebGL) WHATWG (W3C spinoff—we’ll come to it later)\nUnderlying layer(s): • IETF, etc.</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-2.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_SFeIbS",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>Particularities of web standards • Specs mainly target browser vendors (aka implementors) which are handful of huge corporations. • Some are also aimed at “authors” (everyone that creates content on the web, i.e.: content providers and web devs). • End-users aren’t really represented. • Creates important power imbalance.</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-3.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_4ZN6Tr",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>W3C Organization • Royalty-free patent policy (key value prop.). • Structured in working-groups arranged around topics and IP concerns. • Working groups composed of W3C members. • Consensus-based. • Very-much IETF inspired. • Chairs/Editors.</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-4.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_gt5uMG",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>W3C Process\nhttps://www.w3.org/Consortium/Process/</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-5.jpg",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_JCoiEf",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": ""
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-6.jpg",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_vWXW74",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>“A do-ocracy is an organizational structure in which individuals choose roles and tasks for themselves and execute them. Responsibilities attach to people who do the work, rather than elected or selected officials.” https://communitywiki.org/wiki/DoOcracy</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-7.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_XqGJzT",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>Do-ocracy typically evolves spontaneously in groups where: • • • • •\nStakes are low (for those corporations). Authority is non-coercive (no one reports to W3C). Work is plentiful Effort is rewarded with recognition. Culture of participation https://communitywiki.org/wiki/DoOcracy</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-8.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_A9z7rs",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>Dangers • Burnout • Despotism • Frustration (you’re powerless unless you <em>do</em>) • Lack of transparency (de facto vs. de jure) • Resentment (“no one else is working but me”) • Martyrdom Complex (“I’m sacrificing X, you must too”) • Complacency (“someone else will do it”) • Social Exclusion (“only those who <em>do</em>, get a voice”) https://communitywiki.org/wiki/DoOcracy</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-9.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_mThvkH",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": ""
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-10.jpg",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_OnQjcg",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>Browsers have changed • Distribution (boxed software to internet-based continuous deployment) • New versions used to be shipped at best in 18 months cycles (even worse post first browser war). • Now evergreen browsers (auto-update, 6 weeks cycles) • Adoption is a lot faster, which means it’s now possible to consider deprecating features, experimenting. • Feedback loop is much tighter =&gt; innovation!</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-11.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_179XV5",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>…and so has the way they’re built! • FOSS • Continuous integration • Collaborative tools (e.g. GitHub)</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-12.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_dQsLNU",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>Which in turns influences how standards are made.\nhttps://www.w3.org/Consortium/Process/</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-13.jpg",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_Fkb9Ft",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>Consequences Standards stay in WD mode for much longer. Living standard (WHAT WG). Convergence with FOSS (tooling, IP). Criteria for triggering IP commitments (REC status) no longer met. • SDOs who want to stay in the game need to find new solutions. • • • •</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-14.png",
                                    "html": null
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sl_s4Jx8I",
                                    "type": "image",
                                    "title": null,
                                    "desc": {
                                        "html": "<p>Conclusion • For the web, standardization is a do-ocracy. • Steep learning curve + costs puts the web in the hands of the browser vendors. • As standardization moves closer to FOSS, this increases. • Related IP issues need to be solved. • So far, market forces have sort of worked. • Is that sustainable? Should we care? • If so, how do we fix it? (Hint: not with a cookie law.)</p>\n"
                                    },
                                    "image": "https://on.notist.cloud/slides/deck1938/large-15.png",
                                    "html": null
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
